column78: There were two bouts of Male Chorus detected, with the first bout being followed by Female Chatter, indicating a bout of Incubation. Approximately 26 days after the cessation of Male Chorus, the first Fledgling Begging Calls are heard, which correlates perfectly with the expected date if Incubation started just after the cessation of the first bout of Male Chorus (31-May). Onset of the second bout of Male Chorus coincides with the expected onset of Brooding (12-Jun). I have noted that many colonies have a burst of Male Chorus right at onset of Brooding.
column84: Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014. In 2015, they were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded. The colony has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since. Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.

column78: An initial nesting attempt progressed into early Brooding but was abandoned shortly thereafter, as indicated by a brief presence of Begging Calls followed by a sharp decline in vocal activity. Two subsequent nesting attempts occurred later in the season and each showed a complete sequence of Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls. The spacing and partial overlap of these attempts support classification as Complex, and Fledgling Begging Calls confirm successful reproduction in the latter two attempts.

column78: Although a small number of Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations were detected early in the deployment, they declined rapidly, and neither Female Chatter nor Begging Calls occurred at sufficient levels to indicate colony establishment. column84: Tricolored Blackbirds nested in a 0.2-ha patch of Himalayan blackberry in a small area designated as open space surrounded by roadways, commercial stores, parking lots, and a housing development. Commercial and residential construction occurred within 80 m of the nesting site in 2018, and construction activities continued during the breeding period.

column78: The recorder was deployed after breeding had already progressed beyond incubation. Only a small number of Hatchling Begging Calls were detected, followed by a rapid cessation of all Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations. The brief presence of dependent-young vocalizations, followed by complete acoustic absence, indicates that the breeding attempt failed shortly after hatching, consistent with abandonment. A small rain event coincided with the date of hatching though the decline in Female Chatter preceded the rain event. Reason for the Abandonment are unknown.

column84: A series of small copses of Himalayan blackberry alongside Yankee Slough. Most of the blackberry is on a private conservation preserve, Yankee Slough Preserve, that is closed to the public and accessible only with permission.

column78: Fledgling Begging Calls were detected early in the deployment that likely originated from an adjacent portion of the colony where fledging had already begun. Later-stage Begging Calls reflected the attempt recorded by this ARU. Despite reduced signal quality and incomplete data due to device failure late in the deployment, the presence of Fledgling Begging Calls confirms successful reproduction. The colony was adjacent to an active wetland mitigation construction project, though construction was halted around the colony during the breeding period and did not appear to affect breeding success.

column80: The first bout of breeding had some asynchrony, demonstrated bythe presence of Female Chatter for seven days after the onset of Brooding. There is also evidence of a Replacement bout of breeding, though the amount of Female Chatter is very minimal, and if the breeding attempt existed beyond the date the ARU was pulled, would have resulted in only a small number of nests. The ARU was retrieved on approximately the date this second weak Replacement bout of eggs would have hatched. If the 2nd breeding bout had been productive, I estimate that Incubating started on approximately 30-May (end of Male Chorus), and Brooding started on approximately 10-Jun, and fledging on approximately 24-Jun. column79:
This deployment is considered a duplicate dataset of 2021 Willey Wetlands 3. 
The ARU was placed at the periphery of an extensive wetland that also hosted a large White-faced Ibis colony. TRBL vocalizations were present but often faint, and female and early nestling calls were partially masked. Despite this, a clear progression from Nestling to Fledgling Begging Calls indicated successful reproduction. A decline in detections on 7 July coincided with dispersal dates observed in adjacent ARUs and suggests that birds near this recorder represented a slightly later portion of the larger colony.
column80: Manually analyzed data. Large Ibis colony very loud. Recorder appears to be a little distant to where the Tricolored Blackbirds are, but I can her the vocalizations. Many are too faint for template analysis, so a mini manual, followed by edge analysis was performed. Recorder was placed after settlement. Somewhere around when they fail you can hear what I believe might be the other part of the colony right as they are about to fledge. I also think I hear a lot of EUST around this time. There were lots of nestlings up until about 7/6-7/7. Then there is just one or two that hang on. I am calling it a failure at the 7/7ish date. Interestingly this is the date that the other two colonies fledged. My take is that this area was a late attempt compared to the other two areas. And that the majority of the nestlings were old enough to join the crowd when the rest of the colony left the area. Template worked marginally for MS and NC and did not work at all for FS.FS couldn't be located using template analysis. Did mark presence of Female Song when reviewing recordings, so last date here is from these manually reviewed recordings. Recorder was placed just before hatching date, so no Male Chorus. Manual analysis.

Field observations noted nesting activity prior to ARU placement, but by the time recording began, only a few males remained, consistent with the absence of colony formation.
column80: AudioMoth "H", 2 weeks prior to placement of the recorder the site had a lot of Tricolored Blackbirds (audio recording 4/29/2021 10:28). Email from Amy "4/14/2021: "On 4/12/2021 I observed nesting behavior at one of our CNLM preserves in Alameda County.  There were about 100 birds; some of them were carrying nesting material in their beaks". Only one Tricolored Blackbird seen at time of deployment (audio recording 4/29/2021 10:28). Email from Amy 7/14/2021: "I'm afraid this site probably didn't pan out for our Tricolored Blackbird after all, sadly.  When I deployed, there were over 100 trikes, but by the second visit they had decamped and only a dozen remained, then finally only one lonely male who was getting chased off the marsh by RWBBs."
column84: Site is an approx. 4500 sq. meter (1.2 acre) stock pond within a ~400 acre grassland matrix that also hosts California Red-legged Frog, California Tiger Salamander, and seasonal waterfowl. Surrounding land uses are ranching and horse boarding. There is a shooting range nearby (you may hear shots). I noted about 100 Tricolored Blackbirds at the pond April 12. Unfortunately when I returned to place the recorder, they appear to have been supplanted by Red-winged Blackbirds. I observed one male Tricolored Blackbird that was chased off the pond by a male Red-winged Blackbird a few times.

There were about 100 birds; some of them were carrying nesting material in their beaks". Only one Tricolored Blackbird seen at time of deployment (audio recording 4/29/2021 10:28). When I deployed, there were over 100 trikes, but by the second visit they had decamped and only a dozen remained, then finally only one lonely male who was getting chased off the marsh by RWBBs."

column78: Male Song and Male Chorus were readily detected, while Female Chatter and early nestling calls were faint. Manual review revealed multiple Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls over a sustained period, consistent with normal Brooding. Although Fledgling Begging Calls were not detected, the presence of Nestling Begging Calls were detected for greater than 14 days, it is assumed the young fledged and immediately dispersed.
column80: Really really small. Only a few vocalizations noted. Nestling never gets to a full fledged Call. Nestling is heard for 14 days, so assumed to have successfully fledged, But if it did stick around I hear zero fledgling calls. But with the lack of numbers I wonder if this would actually be what would happen. THat is if there is one Fledgling, with no one else to hang out with, you might disperse immediately. Required manual of core. Very small number. Dates are estimates due to scarcity of recordings with vocalizations. Because of this very intermittent vocalizations. Uncertain if the one/couple of nestlings that I do hear made it to fledging. Male chorus was difficult to analyze, I think I might be picking up the adjacent large colony that settled at 27-2 and then largely abandoned. The large colony arrived on 10-May at 7pm.
column84: Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014. In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since. Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking. Additional details are available upon request.
column86: Jennifer Isola, Michael Derrico, Mike Carpenter

column78: Male Song and Male Chorus increased in mid-May, followed by limited Female Chatter, indicating reduced recruitment. The recorder failed shortly after the onset of Brooding, preventing determination of colony type. Although automated Pattern Matching detected no Nestling Begging Calls, manual review of the recordings revealed a small number of Nestling Begging Calls, confirming that hatching had occurred. The fact that these calls were detectable only through manual analysis suggests that the colony was Partially Abandoned at the time the ARU failed. Because the recorder ceased functioning, it is unknown if the colony was fully abanoned or if any of the surviving nestlings fledged. Prolonged extreme heat is the most likely contributing factor, with five consecutive days exceeding 95 °F, including two days above 107 °F, occurring just after hatching.
column80: Required manual of core data. Large group showed for settling, but only a handful stayed for nesting. There are a couple of male songs before the settling that I have confirmed are real. Battery failed just days after hatching. Could not confirm successful fledging
column84: Audio Moth #58 was deployed on a levee road between Tract 27.2 and Tract 27.3 of Colusa National Wildlife Refuge (NWR), just south of the 2021 colony that lies within T27.2.  Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014.  In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since.  Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.

column78: The majority of vocal activity followed a synchronous pattern consistent with a Simple colony structure. A small number of late Nestling Begging Calls extended beyond the main fledging period, indicating limited asynchronous nesting by a few pairs. These detections represented a minor component of overall colony activity and did not alter the primary classification. Sustained Fledgling Begging Calls confirm successful reproduction.
column84: Multiple Himalayan blackberry patches interspersed with cattails and bulrushes exist along the creek west of the road. Four patches are colony locations, 60-200 yards from parkway, each along the canal. The creek flows just north of a housing development.

column78: Acoustic detections showed a clean, synchronous nesting bout with well-defined transitions between vocalization stages. One continuous sequence of Begging Calls led into a predictable Fledging pulse, with no evidence of a second cohort or disturbance.
column84: An emergent marsh dominated by narrow-leaf cattail and bulrush, fed by a narrow stream flowing through riparian woodland dominated by phreatophytic plants including Fremont cottonwood and red willow, and herbaceous understory plants such as salt grass and alkali heath. The colonies in 2021 occurred primarily along the western half of this wetland. A prescribed burn was conducted in this area on February 7th, 2020.

column78: A clear burst of Settlement activity occurred early in the deployment, followed by a sharp reduction in vocalizations as most birds left the area. A small number of birds remained and successfully fledged young, producing a faint but distinct pulse of Fledgling Begging Calls. Reduced abundance and compressed Brooding and Fledging signatures are consistent with Partial Abandonment.
column84: An emergent marsh dominated by narrow-leaf cattail and bulrush, fed by a narrow stream flowing through riparian woodland dominated by phreatophytic plants including Fremont cottonwood and red willow, and herbaceous understory plants such as salt grass and alkali heath. The colonies in 2021 occurred primarily along the western half of this wetland. A prescribed burn was conducted in this area on February 7th, 2020.
column92: 2021 Panoche Creek Preserve 2 East: These were definitely in the same colony. 1E had much better data

column78: Two overlapping but internally synchronous breeding cohorts were detected. The second cohort initiated nesting approximately three weeks after the first, earlier than expected for a Multiple colony structure and before fledglings from the initial cohort had fully dispersed. The temporal overlap and acoustic separation of the two cohorts support classification as Additions rather than Multiple. Fledgling Begging Calls were detected from both cohorts, confirming successful reproduction.
column80: Pulse one over laps pulse 2, such that the YNC of pulse 2 over lap with ONC of pulse 1. There is a drop in ONC starting the 25th, suggesting that a group dispersed on this date. Edge analysis of the first pulse shows evidence of a possible weak pulse before this first one that is recorded. The second pulse has YNC starting consistently on 5/24. Cleaned up the NC templates to better stick with the age range by insisting that the sonogrms more closely look like the template. Hear a consistent but very infrequent nestling call all the way to start (need to finish going back in time on edge to prove this is true)
column84: The site consists of several adjacent clumps of Himalayan blackberry just east of Industrial Avenue, about 1/4 mile south of Twelve Bridges Rd. NEED: This site description is from the TRBL Portal and doesn't match the GPS coordinates.

column78: This deployment is considered a duplicate dataset of 2021 Willey Wetlands 3.
column79:
This deployment is considered a duplicate dataset of 2021 Willey Wetlands 3.  
Despite substantial background noise from ibis, all TRBL vocalizations were detected reliably. The ARU captured the onset of Brooding and produced a strong, uninterrupted sequence of Begging Calls through Fledging. This site displayed a typical synchronous nesting attempt.
column84: See 2021 Willey Wetlands 3.

column78: This deployment is considered the core dataset for the Willey Wetlands group as it provided the most robust detections. Pattern matching for all six vocalizations worked well at this site despite the background of nesting ibis. ARU was placed during the incubation phase and captured the very first Hatchling Begging Calls.
column80: Dispersal day was 7/5-7/6 there were a few nestlings that lingered past this date. I marked 6/21/2021 as last Female Song as I located some during manual analysis of nestling call. I relyed on this because template for Female found very few recordings with Female Song present.
column84: Recorder is placed at the edge of a perennial wetland that was created for the benefit of Giant Garter Snakes. The record is facing west, across a wide channel, towards a colony in thick tules and cattails which is also being occupied by a very large White-faced Ibis colony, with the Tricolored Blackbirds diffusely spread throughout the area.  Recorder was placed where a more dense concentration of Tricolored Blackbirds were observed, but perhaps only a few hundred at this location. This recorder is on the southern side of this particular colony.

column78: Only a small number of Male Song detections were recorded, and no Female Chatter or Begging Calls were detected. Acoustic evidence indicates that breeding was not initiated.
column80: Manual
column84: Patch of cattails about 70 m long x 8 m wide, along a water channel in a mixed pasture/marsh. The patch is 40 m west of city road. The birds share the patch with Red-winged Blackbird, Brown-headed Cowbird, Great-tailed Grackle, and European Starling (looks like the European Starling use the patch only for roosting).

column78: Only scattered detections of Male Song and Male Chorus were recorded, with no evidence of Female Chatter or dependent young. Acoustic evidence indicates that colony establishment did not occur.
column84: The colony nested in a 0.9-ha, stream-fed pond containing cattails and bulrushes , together covering approximately 60% of the pond. Grassland grazed by cattle surrounds the site.

column78: The colony was very small, and breeding-stage vocalizations were weak and infrequent. Female Chatter and Begging Calls were largely absent from automated detections, but manual review identified a small number of Begging Calls that persisted long enough to indicate successful fledging. Due to the limited number of detections, dates for breeding stages are approximate.
column80: Manual, due to the scarceity of vocalizations reported dates are very apporximate. There are more manually analyzed recordings than in the graphs. They are tagged "reviewed-WS". Also called hatch day for the colony with only 2 rec=present due to small size of the colony. There were 2 recordings with Male Chorus that are timed correctly with Onset of Incubation, so I am using these as the dates. With more manual analysis by listening to more recordings I might be able to firm this up, but only do after all others. So few birds there was never a male chorus mid-day. There were a couple of mornings with Male Chorus at 8am.
column84: Natural riparian forest, the Tricolored Blackbird colony is located in a patch of mulefat and stinging nettle. The colony is surrounded by red willows in the north and west, and by a pasture to the east. The recorder was placed on a T-post in an opening adjacent to the colony at 2 m high.

column78: Only sporadic Male Song detections were recorded, with no Female Chatter or Begging Calls present. Mini-manual analysis confirmed the absence of breeding activity.
column80: Manual
column84: Bulrush pond surrounded by red willows at south, southwest, north, northeast, and east. Surrounded by rabbitbrush at west and northwest. Adjacent to the rabbitbrush, there are large Fremont cottonwood trees, 20 m tall.

column78: Vocal activity declined rapidly by mid-May, and all Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations ceased shortly thereafter. The abrupt cessation of activity indicates abandonment prior to fledging.
column80: Colony abandoned on 14-May.  Recorder was pulled 20-May for reuse at another site. There were three consecutive days of temperatures above 90 from 11 May to 13 May which could be the reason for abandonment. There is a single recording which has a potential Tricolored Blackbird nestling vocalization, though it is brief, and I am not certain that it is truly a Tricolored Blackbird nestling. Also, there is a Red-winged Blackbird adult in this recording as well, so it could just be a Red-winged Blackbird nestling. ARU was redeployed at Conaway Ranch.
column84: See 2021 Reeds Creek South.

column78: Breeding-stage vocalizations were detected clearly, including Hatchling Begging Calls followed by strong Fledgling Begging Calls. The sequence and timing of calls indicate a single synchronous breeding attempt that successfully fledged young.
column80: The ARU was placed after Male Chorus had started. Fledgling Begging Calls are not present for the entire day starting June 30th, so I have marked fledging day as June 29th, though there are a few fledglings in the recordings through July 2nd. NOTE - REMOVE MINI MANUAL TAGS HERE. THEY WERE NOT COMPLETE, AND THE ANALYSIS IS NOT NEEDED. WE AN DO THIS BY DELETING THE TAG IN THE EXCEL SHEET WE GOT FROM ARBIMON.

column78: Hatchling Begging Calls were detected briefly, but the ARU was removed shortly thereafter. Limited data precluded determination of whether nestlings survived to fledging.
column80: The ARU was placed right at the end of Male Chorus. Based on the density of vocalizations in the recordings this was a very small colony. The ARU was pulled on the day after the first Hatchling Begging Calls were heard, and there are only 23 recordings found with Hatchling Begging Calls. While this site was largely abandoned, we cannot be certain if the hatchlings heard survived to fledging, or if the site was abandoned altogether. The ARU was redeployed at Conaway Ranch.

column78: The colony was extremely small, and detections were limited to a small number of recordings. Hatchling Begging Calls were detected briefly, indicating that hatching occurred, but Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls were sparse and short-lived. The rapid decline in activity following early Brooding is consistent with Partial Abandonment. Breeding-stage dates are approximate due to the low number of detections.
column80: Manual. This colony was extremely small. The dates are extremely rough and based on just a few recordings which contained Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations. Male Chorus was never robust. I set hatch date for the colony based on last Female Song. Tagged recordings failed to detect the youngest nestlings. However I did loacte a few that I am certain of on 5/8 and 5/10.
column84: The colony is in a patch of stinging nettle (old and new), next to a young patch of skinny Fremont cottonwoods in the north, and next to a pasture in the south. The recorder was placed in a cottonwood at 2.2 m high.

column78: Female Chatter was detected briefly early in the deployment, indicating initiation of nest building. The rapid loss of vocal activity indicates that breeding was abandoned shortly after initiation, and no colony established.
column80: Abandoned, battery ran out on last days so just spot checked on recordings I did have to confirm lack of presence, males were showing up off and on starting in Feb, so I didn't have to do all as edge I cherry picked recordings with the MC present, these are just marked as reviewed-WS. Females only sang for a couple of days before colony abandoned. There were isolated Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations after 4/22/2021, but these were scarce after 4/22.
column84: Tricolored Blackbirds nested in a 0.2-ha patch of Himalayan blackberry in a small area designated as open space surrounded by roadways, commercial stores, parking lots, and a housing development.

column78: Female Chatter was followed by a coherent progression of Hatchling, Nestling, and Fledgling Begging Calls. There was a mid-deployment gap in data when there were no recordings collected. A manual review of recordings just prior to this gap confirmed Hatchling Begging Calls, allowing date of hatching to be determined. Fledgling Begging Calls declined abruptly following Dispersal, confirming successful reproduction from a single synchronous breeding attempt.
column80: Recorder was turned off on May 15 and then turned back on on May 22. Luckily we are still able to determine hatch date. There is an odd set of ONC much after fledging day. June 20ish. I suspect this is the roaming band of fledglings that have returned to the area and are hanging out in the habitat.

column86: Daisy Carrillo, Travis Bibee, Melissa Dabulamanzi, Landon Peppel

column78: Breeding progressed to the onset of Brooding, after which Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations declined sharply. No Fledgling Begging Calls were detected. The timing of failure coincided with an extreme heat event, consistent with abandonment during early Brooding.
column80: Manual, Jun 23 last nestling heard, manually analyzed every day. Colony failed during an extreme heat wave that coincided with hatching. There are a couple of Fledgling calls at the very start of the recordings. This suggests that there may have been an earlier pulse that was missed. Extremely rough guess.... estimated hatch for this earlier pulse would have been ~5/15/2021, Fledging day ~5/29/2021, all of which was before the placement of the recorder. Though these sound a little "funny" so might be a different species.
column84: Unit placed on the levee surrounding Bridge St. Pond on the San Jacinto Wildlife Area. To the west is private land with perennial ryegrass hay and alfalfa. To the south is the pond which is surrounded by a narrow band of willows and mulefat, and has a dense growth of cattails and bulrush in the pond itself. Beyond the pond is weedy fallow fields. To the east is Mystic Lake bed, mostly grown up in tall forbs, native and non-native. To the north is SJWA irrigated, weedy fields.
column90: 2021 San Jacinto Wildlife Area - Bridge Street Pond

column79: Pattern matching and manual review confirmed the absence of all Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations. Although the site had supported colonies in previous years, no colony formed in 2021.
column80: Manually analyzed data to confirm no birds present by doing 3 recordings (8am,11am,2pm) every thrid day. Also did template analysis for MS and FS with no hits found.
column84: The nesting colony used several patches of Himalayan blackberry, totaling approximately 0.6 ha, along Markham Ravine Creek. The site was surrounded by cultivated rice fields, open grassland, and a former irrigated hayfield that was converted to a wetland mitigation site during 2018.
column87: no longer there, email Charlotte Marks instead

column78: Female Chatter persisted well beyond the onset of Brooding, consistent with asynchronous nest initiation. Two distinct pulses of Hatchling, Nestling, and Fledgling Begging Calls were detected, indicating two temporally separated breeding attempts. The fact that this colony exhibited both Asynchrony and a Multiple colony type support classification as Complex. Fledgling Begging Calls confirm successful reproduction in both attempts.
column79: Female Chatter persisted well beyond the onset of Brooding, consistent with asynchronous nest initiation. Two distinct pulses of Hatchling, Nestling, and Fledgling Begging Calls were detected, indicating two temporally separated breeding attempts. The fact that this colony exhibited both Asynchrony and a Multiple colony type support classification as Complex. Fledgling Begging Calls confirm successful reproduction in both attempts.
column80: Asynchronous, if there was Male Chorus it was before recorder was placed. Appears to be a continuosly nesting colony in that there is no pulsing to the Female Song and Female Song continues for a long time after fisrst hatchlings are heard. There are two rounds of fledgling dispersal. One on 6/1 and the other on 6/16. Of course uncertain if the gap is caused by the creche leaving and returning or if it is a second group of late hatchers that make up the second pulse of Fledglings.
column84: A Himalayan blackberry patch, 20 m long x 5 m wide, adjacent to a paved highway in a public right of way. There is a water channel and pasture with cows present adjacent to the blackberry patch to the north. The recorder was placed inside the colony, on the east side, at 1 m high. The recorder will pick up significant road noise at this site.

column79: Neither automated nor manual analyses detected any Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations, indicating absence of birds at the site during the recording window.
column80: Manual, accidentlly did every day rather than every third
column84: Small pond with dormant cattails. The landowner mentioned raccoon predators in previous years; no Tricolored Blackbird present when unit was deployed. The landowner is James McCutcheon, email gwschool@wildblue.net

column78: Only a small number of Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations were detected, and activity declined rapidly. Both automated and manual analyses indicate that all vocalizations ceased by early June, consistent with abandonment. Limited detections precluded confident assignment of breeding-stage chronology.
column80: If there was Male Chorus it was before recorder was placed. Hatch day for colony only had 5 rec w/ YNC present, but since this was a small colony I accepted a smaller number of present to indicate hatch day. Colony failed and last Tricolored Blackbird vocalization was heard on 6/5/2021.
column84: Riparian forest composed of old Fremont cottonwood and red willow trees and many young Fremont cottonwood trees (< 3 m tall). The ground is covered mainly by grass (alkali rye) with many patches of dead and new stinging nettle. There are also some areas with mulefat. The colony of Tricolored Blackbird is ~60 m from an irrigation channel and ~100 m from the South Fork Kern River. Colony area is owned by Audubon Kern River Preserve, but not open to the public.

column78: Female Chatter, Hatchling Begging Calls, and Fledgling Begging Calls overlapped in the earliest recordings, indicating that breeding was already underway at the time of ARU deployment. The concurrence of Brooding and Dispersal-stage vocalizations supports an Asynchronous colony structure. Fledgling Begging Calls declined sharply by late May, marking dispersal and confirming successful reproduction.
column80: Very small colony, needed manual analysis. Hear fledglings at the beginning, so appears that this was placed after a successful first round. Because of this I have marked the pulse that has hatchlings as pulse 2. There are very few vocalizations, and the last nestling call I hear is on 6/9/2022. These vocalizations are distant to the recorder, and don't quite sound like fledglings. Because of this, I can't be certain that the young from this second pulse successfully fledged, though their vocalizations are heard 13 days after initial hatchling calls are heard, so I suspect that they did.
column83: Bulrush or tule, Cattails, Common Reed
column84: Wetland complex on private agricultural and ranch lands surrounded by levee road. Tricolored Blackbirds were first detected in WA in 1998. In 1999, a bird was detected near this site, and the location has had regular reports most years since. It is unclear if anyone had located this colony prior to my efforts this year, or for how long this actual colony site has been used. It seems they have nested in the area somewhere and somewhat regularly since colonizing Washington.
column88: Audio on 5/27/2022 confirms time and location as Harder Springs. No email notes.

column78: A small number of Male Song detections were recorded, but Female Chatter and Begging Calls were absent. Acoustic evidence indicates that breeding did not occur, or that any nesting activity was too limited or distant to be detected reliably.
column80: Recorder was set for 1 every 10 min, thus it ran out of battery mid season. A few male song were detected, but no other Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations were detected. So either no colony formed or if the colony did form it was too distant and or too small to be detected by the ARU.
column83: Bulrush or tule, Cattails, Himalayan blackberry
column84: Strapped to a fence post bordering the colony.  Ten feet off a country road

column78: Two temporally distinct nesting attempts were detected, each with asynchronous breeding. The first bout of breeding was partially abandoned, and rain shortly after hatching could have been the cause. Female Chatter isn't detected prior to the hatching of the second bout of nestlings, possibly because of the background vocalizations of the asynchronous colony drowning them out.
column80: Colony is all over the place, but I am documenting the 2 pulses that seem the most prevalent. The first pulse isn't large. The Dispersal date was assigned because I noted a couple of recordngs with much higher density of Fledgling calls, so a little spike. I marked the highes t density recording with the tage Fledgling Dispersal. I still need to analyze the second pulse. I believe that there are two asynchronous pulses. The first HD 4/12-4/15, the second HD ~<5/22/-6/1. Or it is a continuously laying colony.
column84: The Hay Landfill colony site is in a mitigation pond adjacent to the Hay Road Landfill in Vacaville, Solano County, California (38.306, −121.825) at 6.5 m elevation. The colony nested in a 7.0-ha, water-managed pond containing tule covering approximately 25% of the pond. The colony is surrounded by agricultural land and grassland on the eastern, western, and southern borders and a landfill on the northern border. A heavily traveled highway borders the eastern edge.

column78: An initial synchronous breeding attempt was followed approximately three weeks later by the arrival of an additional cohort, resulting in overlapping breeding stages. The Addition masked portions of the first attempt’s Brooding and Dispersal signals, but two distinct peaks of Fledgling Begging Calls were detected. Both cohorts progressed through fledging, confirming successful reproduction for each attempt.
column80: Sub-colony addition. After the first birds established a larger group appears to have joined them, resulting in overlapping breeding stages.  Based on density of nestling calls the second addition of birds was significanly larger than the first. The hatching date for the colony for pulse 1 is estimated, as the onset of pulse 2 Male Chorus drowns out the nestlings. So dates marked as nestling call not present when there is the loud male chorus are likely just because I can't hear them. When I do finally hear them, it is obvious that they are older nestlings. A few nestlings were heard on 5/17, and with most colonies the majority of hatching happens the day after first nestlings are heard, so I estimate that hatching date is ~5/18. The Fledgling dispersal date of pulse 1 is also an estimate as the calls from pulse 2 nestlings make it hard to determine the exact date. For recordings that were analyzed to determine the edge of hatching and dispersal (p1n, p2n) where the two pulaes overlapped I have marked the YNC with the tag YNC-p2 and the older nestling calls with ONC-p1 to distinguish between the two pulses of nestlings. I picked the p1 dispersal date on the day that seemed to have a lull in the ONC. There is a temporary lull in p2 nestling calls 6/12-6/13. There was also a rain storm on that day which maybe explains the lull. The majority of the nestlings disperse on 7/3/2022 (last day with high volume of NCs), but stragglers can be heard thru the end of the recordings. Battery started running out on July 4th and completely died by July 13th.
column84: Isolated pond/spring are approximately 2 acres in size, likely natural spring plus irrigation water. Some open water but mainly mix of Common Reed, bulrush, and cattail. First discovered in 2018 (but could have existed long before) and used each year since.

column78: Two temporally distinct and complete breeding attempts were detected. The first attempt involved a larger number of birds, with high densities of Female Chatter followed by strong Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls. After fledglings from the first attempt dispersed, a second, smaller attempt began, characterized by renewed Male Chorus, Female Chatter, and a full sequence of Begging Calls. Both attempts progressed through fledging and dispersal, confirming successful reproduction.
column80: No male chorus detected. There were periods each morning that had a weak male chourus, but nothing that wasn't above the background of the colony over time.
column84: Mature oak trees in proximity to the colony with some smaller shrubs less than 10 m away from the colony. Besides scattered trees, most of the surrounding vegetation is open grassland.
column88: I deployed the ARU this year, and observed about 600 birds which came into the marsh in the evening and departed early the next morning, presumably to feed.

column78: Nestling Begging Calls were present in the first recordings, indicating breeding was already underway at deployment. Two distinct pulses of Fledgling Begging Calls spaced approximately one month apart indicate two breeding attempts occurring against a background of asynchronous activity. Both attempts produced fledglings.
column80: Nestlings are detected on the very first day that the ARU was placed. This site had continuous Male Chorus, suggesting Asynchronous colony type. However, you can also see that there is also a hint that there is a Multiple bout of breeding in that there are two bouts of fledglings that are spaced approximately 30 days apart. From the density of detections, it appears that the second Multiple bout of breeding was larger than the first bout.
column84: NEED

column78: This ARU captured a more synchronous portion of the larger Plumas Arboga colony. A clear sequence of Begging Calls was detected, and Fledgling Begging Calls confirm successful reproduction.
column80: The ARU was set for 1 every 10 min. While this ARU was placed in the same colony as 2022 Plumas Arboga East, this recorder picked up a section of the colony that had a higher level of synchrony, though you can see a few Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls in early May, similar to the Plumas Arboga East site.
column84: See 2022 Plumas Arboga East.

column80: Only one male song was located in the recordings. Recorder began running out of battery at the end of July.
column84: Audio Moth #60 was deployed on a levee road between Tract 27.2 and Tract 27.1 of Colusa National Wildlife Refuge (NWR), just north of the 2021 colony that lies within T27.2.  Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014.  In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since.  Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.
column86: Jennifer Isola, Michael Derrico, Mike Carpenter

column78: Male Chorus was continuous throughout much of the deployment. This resulted in a low detection of Female Chatter in the pattern matching, therefore a manual analysis was performed. This showed that Female Chatter overlapped extensively with Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls. This prolonged overlap of reproductive stages is characteristic of Asynchronous nesting. Sustained Fledgling Begging Calls confirm successful reproduction.

column84: Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014.  In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since.  Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.

column78: A colony of Tricolored Blackbirds established at this site and completed a successful breeding attempt in Himalayan blackberry. The colony was moderately small, with an estimated 400–500 birds. Nestling Begging Calls were already present in the first recordings, indicating that one nesting attempt was well underway before the ARU was deployed. Hatchling Begging Calls appeared later in the recording period, showing that an additional nesting attempt occurred while the recorder was active. Because the first attempt began before the ARU was in place, the acoustic record cannot distinguish whether the colony’s structure reflects an Addition to the original attempt or Asynchronous nesting. Fledgling Begging Calls developed before the end of the deployment, confirming that the colony produced fledglings successfully.
column79: A colony of Tricolored Blackbirds established at this site and completed a successful breeding attempt in Himalayan blackberry. Nestling Begging Calls were already present in the first recordings, indicating that one nesting attempt was well underway before the ARU was deployed. Hatchling Begging Calls appeared later in the recording period, showing that an additional nesting attempt occurred while the recorder was active. Because the first attempt began before the ARU was in place, the acoustic record cannot distinguish whether the colony’s structure reflects an Addition to the original attempt or Asynchronous nesting among subgroups. Fledgling Begging Calls developed before the end of the deployment, confirming that the colony produced fledglings successfully.

column78: Recording quality at this site was low, with faint detections limiting resolution of early-stage vocalizations such as Female Chatter. However, Fledgling Begging Calls were consistently detectable and revealed four distinct pulses of fledglings. The approximately month-long spacing between pulses is consistent with a Multiple colony structure. Because early-stage vocalizations were poorly resolved, confidence in distinguishing Multiple from Asynchronous patterns is reduced, but available evidence supports classification as Multiple. All attempts produced fledglings.
column79:
The ARU didn't pick up the colony very well and all vocalizations are quite faint. Female Chatter is never heard, but there is almost continuous Male Chorus, and I can barely hear the young. Fledgling Begging Calls, being more strident, were picked up by the ARUs, and analysis of the Fledgling Begging Calls suggests there were two successful bouts of breeding, with the first bout starting with a small group which then had a larger Addition. This lead to the presence of Fledling Begging Calls from 1-May to 6-May (weak first bout), 22-May to 5-Jun (stronger Addition), and 21-Jun tp 24-Jun (Repeat). If this is correct, I can estimate the breeding stages as Bout #1: Incubation started ~6-Apr, Brooding ~16-Apr, and confirmed to have Fledged on 1-May and Dispersed 6-May. There was an addition to this first bout, with this addition starting to Incubate ~28-Apr, Brooding ~8-May, and was confirmed to have Fledged on 22-May and these fledglings hung around until 5-Jun. Once this first bout was completed, a Repeat bout was initiated and Incubation began ~27-May, Brooding ~7-Jun, and Fledging on 21-Jun and stuck around until 24-Jun, after which the majority of the Fledgling Begging Calls cease. There is a long tail of occasional Fledgling Begging Calls that extends through 27-Jul. I do not know if these are stragglers finishing up a really late breeding attempt, or if these are just fledglings that are re-visiting the area occasionally. Mini Manual was completed. 

ISSUE #1: None of the other results that I've reviewed are explicit about restating the dates like this. There's Table 4 in Results that have all the same information. It seems like either all of the sites should have this restated, or none should. 
ISSUE #2: The dates here are different than what's in Table 4. e.g. Table 4 has FBC from 24-May to 5-Jun, above it says 22-May to 5-Jun. Above says Incubation started 6-Apr, 28-Apr, and 27-May, but the table says Before, ND, and ND.

Some alternate wording for the first part: 
The ARU captured the colony poorly, and all vocalizations were faint. Female Chatter never occurred in the recordings, but Male Chorus was nearly continuous, and only faint vocalizations from young were audible. Fledgling Begging Calls, being more strident, carried into the recordings, and their timing suggests two successful bouts of breeding. The first bout began with a small group that was followed by a larger Addition.

ISSUE #3: Remove reference to REPEAT BOUT in the final text, replace with MULTIPLE somehow (could just be "second" and not reference the Multiple, since that word is in the first sentence of the stock paragraph.

ISSUE #4: "Breeding Type" in Col BV is "Async" but above mentions "Repeat" aka Multiple.
column80: The recorder didn't pick up the colony very well and all vocalizations are quite faint. FS is never heard, but there is almost continuous chorus, and I can hear the young. I am betting that the young hatch multiple days before I pick them up on the recording. Analysis of the Fledgling Calls suggests there were two successful pulses, with the first pulse starting with a small group and then a larger sub-colony addition. This lead to a Fledling call from 5/1-5/6, 5/22-6/5, and 6/21-6/24. I can estimate the breeding stages as Pulse #1: There was a pulse that started incubating ~4/6, hatched ~4/16, and confirmed to have fledged on 5/1 - and these fledglings hung around for about until 5/6, so hung out for a total of 6 days. Since the recorder was placed on 4/14 I am unable to document the onset of incubation. Hatchlings are too far away to hear until they get a few days old. First nestlings are heard on  There was a sub-colony addition to this first pulse, with this addition starting incubation ~4/28, hatching ~5/8, and was confirmed to have fledged on 5/22 and these fledglings hung around until 6/5, or 15 days. When marking MC - looked for SOLID bands just above and below 2kHz, because of the distance of the chorusing at times, it looks underwhelming compared to other recordings which have Male Song at a closer distance, but they were not a SOLID band. Pulse #2: Once this first pulse was completed, a Replacement Pulse was initiated and incubation began ~5/27, hatching ~6/7, and this pulse fledged on 6/21 and stuck around until 6/24 for a total of 4 days, when the majority of the fledgling calls cease. There is a long tail of occasional fledgling calls that extends through 7/27. I do not know if these are stragglers finishing up a really late breeding attempt, or if these are just fledglings that are re-visiting the area occasionally. Mini Manual was completed.

column80: Recordings were faint, but usable. First round of birds started inc on 5/7, then second addition came in on 5/10. First birds would have hatched at ~5/18 (works), then second addition would have hatched ~5/23. 2nd round was much larger, their fledge date would have been ~6/3 (works). So there is one messy pulse of breeding that had an addition after first set started incubating. This results in nestlings being heard only a few days after the last Male Chorus.The FC was never impressive, but there was a large drop in vocalizations on 6/4, so this was picked as the FD.
column84: This is an old irrigation pond that still gets water even though the surrounding farmland hasn't been farmed in many years.  The surrounding area is green and vibrant in the spring but bakes yellow once summer arrives.  Photos were taken showing north, south, east, and west views.  The MOTH was placed on a metal fence post bordering the road on the south side of the colony.

column78: Two temporally distinct bouts of Fledgling Begging Calls were detected, separated by approximately one month. Although early-stage vocalizations were faint, the spacing and repetition of fledgling peaks indicate two discrete synchronous breeding attempts. Both bouts produced fledglings, confirming successful reproduction.
column80: There were a few recordings with Male Song, and then at the end of the season a fledgling calls can be heard. Because Pattern Matching did'nt work well a mini-manual analysis was performed, and it also failed to detect Female Chatter and nestling calls. Jason reports that there was a colony of ~100 birds at this location and has an account of food carrying on 5/29. I suspect that for some reason the recorder did not pick up the colony very well, and it only registered the louder vocalizations of the Male Song and Fledgling calls, much like Baja this year. I also suspect that the lack of Male Chorus is just due to the small number of birds. Unfortunately, the lack of robust vocalizations make it so I can't tell much from this site. Based on Fledgling call alone a super tentative guess would be Fledging day of 6/17, whch would put hatch day at ~6/3, and incubation start at ~5/23. But this doesn't agree with ebird reports or field visits. Though it is just a few days off. If Food carries on 3/29 (in-person) was the date of hatching, and if on the longer end for fledgling (14days) then date of fledging would be 6/12. Also, with feeding of Fladglings still seen on Aug, this could have been a continuous nesting site. If this was a continuous nesting site, with the small number of birds I would have had an even lower number of vcalizations to pick up, and this might be beyond the reach of my analysis detection abilities. Also of note, this site was much later than the McCain Wetlands and timing suggests that this could be the same birds as at McCain Wetlands but their second bout of breeding.

column84: ~2 acre Isolated pond/spring. Likely natural spring plus irrigation water. Some open water but mainly mix of phfrag, bullrush, and cattail. First discovered in 2018 (but could have existed long before) and used each year since.

column78: A small colony established in April but abandoned just after the first hatchlings were heard. Hatchling Begging Calls were only heard for four days, after which the only Tricolored Blackbird vocoalizations noted were a handful of Male Song. Potential reasons for abandonment are unknown.
column79: A small Tricolored Blackbird colony established at this marsh, nested in emergent vegetation including bulrush or tule and cattails, but the attempt was ultimately abandoned. Early in the deployment, Male Chorus activity indicated that males were present and displaying, but the number of singing males decreased over time. The colony progressed into Brooding, as reflected by the onset of that stage during the recording period, yet Fledgling Begging Calls never developed. All Tricolored Blackbird vocal activity ceased abruptly around the time Brooding would be expected to continue, and only a few birds remained thereafter. These patterns indicate that the nesting attempt advanced into early chick-rearing but was abandoned before fledglings were produced. The cause of abandonment is unknown.
column80: Small colony established but then abandoned. Initially there were more males in MC and then it dwindled to fewer birds.
column84: The Los Vaqueros Reservoir colony is located in a 200 sq m patch of Himalayan blackberry that is just uphill from a 900 sq m small pond. The blackberry patch is fenced. Surrounding this area is open grassland with grazing cattle.

column78: Female Chatter persisted throughout the breeding period without a clear break, and Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls overlapped in time. Fledgling Begging Calls confirm successful reproduction, although the outcome of a small number of late hatchings could not be determined.
column80: This was a small asynchronous colony. There are some really young nestlngs heard starting on 14-May that imply that there might be a Replacement bout of breeding, though there are no Female Chatter associated with it. Since I hear some Female Chatter all the way through 4-May I suspect that I am just hearing the "dribbles" from the late nesters. Female Chatter never took a break and the started up again, so in this way it acts more like a Continuously breeding colony, rather than a Replacement. And Female Chatter was a continuous decline from onset of Brooding through 4-May. If the hatchlings I hear on 14-May are from the females that are chattering on 2-May it would make them only a couple of days old. The bulk of the breeding was finished by the end of the month and the fledglings dispersed. It is unknown if the handful of late hatchings survived to fledging.

column78: While the bulk of the breeding was simple and synchronous, there is a long tail with a few straggling vocalizations that suggest that there may have been a handful of either Asynchronous breeding or a Multiple bout of breeding. For example there is a single Female Chatter on 29-Jun as well a Fledgling Begging Call is 7-Jul. I have assigned a Simple breeding pattern as this describes the vast majority of birds.
column79: The breeding attempt was predominantly synchronous, producing a clear sequence of Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls. A small number of late detections, including isolated Female Chatter and a single late-season Fledgling Begging Call, suggest the presence of a few asynchronous or late-start nests. However, these represented only a minor portion of colony activity, and the overall pattern aligns with a Simple colony structure. Fledgling Begging Calls were abundant and confirm successful reproduction.

Important notes from Dave in email "I haven’t been following the tricolors nearly as much as last spring, so it was a big surprise to me to see hundreds of tricolors crossing Davis Road this afternoon.  I estimated 1,240 adults and about 300 fledglings, nesting along the San Jacinto River channel west of Davis, feeding lepidopterous larvae almost exclusively while I was there.  Foraging flocks were just across Davis all the way out to the Burrowing Owl fields.  There is a second nesting attempt underway there as well.  Dave"

column84: Permanent pond rimmed with bulrushes and previously with patchy bulrush in the center of the pond, drowned out due to high water in Spring 2023. The riparian area and pond are surrounded by dry rangeland of grasses and shrubs, notably California buckwheat.

column78: A large Tricolored Blackbird colony, estimated at roughly 2,000 birds, established at this reservoir site in Himalayan blackberry and exhibited a Complex breeding structure showing both Asynchronous and Multiple colony types. The first attempt was Asynchronous: Male Chorus continued through Incubation, Female Chatter overlapped with the period when fledglings were present, and Fledgling Begging Calls showed a prolonged tail, indicating that different portions of the colony were at different breeding stages at the same time. After fledglings from this first attempt dispersed, a second, Asynchronous nesting attempt occurred. Asynchronous was assigned due to the continuation of Female Chatter after Hatchling Begging Calls were heard. Based on the density of vocalizations, the second attempt was much smaller than the first. Both attempts produced fledglings, and the overall outcome for the site was Successful.
column79: A large Tricolored Blackbird colony, estimated at roughly 2,000 birds, established at this reservoir site in Himalayan blackberry and exhibited a Complex breeding structure showing both Asynchronous and Multiple colony types. column80: This was a highly asynchronous colony. Based on what I hear I believe this was one with a continual expansion/egg laying in each pulse rather than a sub-colony addition. The asynchrony made it challenging to determine MC for pulse 2 asn well as HD for pulse 2. For MC2 I looked for signs of MS at just above Khz 2, and have put a p2c tag at where this band is for many of the recordings. For HD2 I relyed on PMJs to locate recordings with signals of very young nestlings. I then focused on these dates and zoomed in so 8-0 Ktz and about 4 sec were showing on the sonogram. I then looked visually for the signature of very young nestings. It was too hard to try and use my ears to decide if it was a very young nestling or a late nesting from pulse 1.

column84: Cattail marsh surrounded by pasture land.  The recorder was placed on a fence post next to the marsh on the south end.

column78: Fledgling Begging Calls were present at the start of the deployment, indicating that a first breeding attempt had already progressed to fledging. After fledglings from this initial attempt dispersed, a second nesting bout occurred, marked by a new onset of Nestling Begging Calls followed by a small number of Fledgling Begging Calls late in the deployment. Although the second attempt involved few birds, the temporal separation between the two fledging pulses supports classification as Multiple, and both attempts produced fledglings, though the second attempt was partially abandoned. In-person visits confirmed the partial abandonment. Destruction of the nesting substrate, desicating milk thistle falling over, likely explain the Partial Abandonment.
column80: It appears that the recorder was placed well into the first pulse, and that there were a decent number of young fledged. While the FD is only 7 days from when the recorder was placed, since there is countinouous Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations past this date, it is assumed that pulse 1 fledged successfully. There is a very weak p2 with only a couple of young heard. These are heard throughout the recordings and vocalizations on the last day are of an older youngster, and it is >14 days from hatch date of p2, so while this was extremelt minor, it was also successful.
column84: The ARU was placed very close to the colony, alongside the milk thistle in some tall grass. The colony is in milk thistle patches alongside a canal ditch that had water. There was some mugwort along the canal as well.

column78: A few Fledgling Begging Calls detected during the first recordings indicates either a fledgling is traveling with the adults or there was a bout of breeding prior to the placement of the ARU. Female Chatter in June indicates a bout of breeding, and Nestling Begging Calls were detected in July, followed by Fledgling Beggging calls. The number of Nestling Begging Calls compared to Female Chatter indicate that there was likely a modest partial abandonment, though it is just below the threshold I am using for calling an attempt Partially Abandoned. In-person visits confirmed that the birds nesting in the milk thistle abandoned when the nesting substrate dried up and fell over, whereas the birds nesting in the willows successfully fledged young.
column80: Colony was on the smaller side. Because of this, I used >=3 present to determine hatch day.
column84: The birds nested in the willows and buttonbush in the river channel as well as the milk thistle along the levee. The birds in the milk thistle abandoned early (June 20) after the milk thistle dried up and fell over. I placed the recorder under some of the willow trees in mud near the water, I think the nests closest to the recorder abandoned. The colony successfully fledged chicks.

column78: Although colony size was small and early-stage vocalizations were weak, Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls were detected. The timing of fledgling vocalizations indicates successful reproduction by a small number of pairs.
column80: There was one very small bout. There was hardly any Male Chorus, with a stutter start 7-Apr and 8-APr but it was not followed by Female Chatter. The second bout of Male Chorus was extremely short, and likely only a few males remained. Only a handful of Nestling Begging Calls are detected, and there is a period of time where no Nestling Begging Calls are detected, but it is followed by some Fledgling Begging Calls that are timed such that these are likely the Fledglings from this colony. So while the bulk of birds did not Settle, there were a handful that did and successfully fledged young.

column78: Pattern matching detected robust vocalizations throughout the breeding cycle. A brief period of strong Fledgling Begging Calls in mid-July was attributed to fledglings from the adjacent colony at T27.2. Later, a lighter pulse of Fledgling Begging Calls corresponded to the colony at this location. The timing of both pulses indicates that adults from T27.2 initiated a subsequent nesting attempt at T27.1, and this later attempt successfully fledged young.
column80: It appears that a few fledglings from T27.1 are heard here in T27.1 just after they fledged, confusing analysis. These older birds are not the end of an earlier pulse in T27.1 because there is no evidence of Female Chatter, YNC, or MNC at all in the recordings evn though the recorder was placed with sufficient time to capture these vocalizations if they had been there. Therefore, I am only documenting a single pulse at this location, though because the ON from the other location are around, I need to document this as p2 to tease the two sets of nestlings apart. Additionally, there may be straggler p1 nestlings in the recordings as well, as they don't quite sound like fledglings to me in all of the recordings where I hear ONC when I "shouldn't". Interestingly, I believe that the birds from T27.2 have shifted their second attempt to T27.1 rather than do a replacement pulse in T27.2 and reusing previous nesting areas, thus the marking as p2 would be appropriate. The number of breeding birds is tiny in this pulse. By the end there are just a few straggling nestlings that can be heard to the end of the recordings. I did manage to document at least one fledgling on 7/27/2023 making the Fledgling calls, and I marked these as Simple Call 2 Present. Many of these calls are starting to take on the Flight-call "yip" sound, but their sonograms are much fuzzier and haven't quite developed the crisp sonogram that the adults have. For making summary excel this "second" pulse has been placed in the "first pulse" slot.
column84: Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014.  In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since.  Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.

column80: This ARU did not pick up the colony well, and the vocalizations are quite weak. This could be due to either distance to the colony or possibly the unit being placed in the dry-box upside down. I have manually assessed recordings for the presence of the youngest Nestlings, and on 19-May I begin to hear faint vocalizations, so this date is listed as the first day Hatchling Begging Calls are heard. Due to the faint vocalizations, it is likely that the eggs hatched several days prior to this date, and that the first Hatchling Begging Calls were not picked up by the ARU. A second bout of breeding was initiated, though there were very few vocalizations detected. Those that are detected indicate that at least a few birds initiated a second bout of breeding. The recorder was pulled just after the first Hatchling Begging Calls were expected. No Hatchling Begging Calls were detected for this second bout of breeding, but given the nature of the poor quality of the recordings, this is not unexpected. Therefore, I have marked the outcome from this bout of breeding as Unknown.

column80: This colony had a Complex form of breeding and exhibited both Sub-colony Addition and Replacement forms. After the first bout of breeding commenced Brooding, there was a Sub-colony Addition on 4-May. These new arrivals would have occupied new nesting sites, as the original individuals that formed the colony were still brooding, and thus nests were occupied. In addition, there was a third bout of Male Chorus that occurs approximately at the time the first Fledgling Begging Calls are heard, that suggest that this is a Replacement bout of breeding where the nesting sites previously occupied are reused for another bout of breeding. This Replacement bout is much smaller than the original bout of breeding, and there are only a handful of Female Chatter in June, and only a few Hatchling Begging Calls in June as well. This second weak bout might have also shown a replacement for the sub-colony addition, though it was hard to document, as it was obscured by the vocalizations from the overlapping, and much larger bout of breeding from the first bout, but the presence of Fledgling Begging Calls into mid-June imply that this Replacement bout of at the orignal nesting sites, was also successful. Additionally, there is evidence that there was a Replacement bout of breeding at the Sub-colony Addition sites in that there are hatchlings heard on June 13, which is 28 days after the hatchlings from the first subcolony addition are heard. NOTE - SHOULD ADD THE BLACK ARROWS FOR EACH OF THE HATCHLING BOUTS ONTO THE CHART.

column78:
Early-season activity is high, with strong Male Chorus throughout March and April. Activity drops abruptly on 25 April. In late April, only a few Female Chatter were detected, indicating that although Male Chorus was strong, just a handful of females were recruited to nest. A site visit on 29 April confirmed this weak recruitment: only ~50 birds remained from the original ~500, and only a few females were carrying food. Sparse Fledgling Begging Calls in late May–mid June indicate that a small number of nests succeeded. There is no date of Dispersal for this bout of breeding. This is because the Fledgling Begging Calls from this bout continue through the onset of the next bout of Fledgling Begging Calls.

A second attempt initiated later in the season and proceeded normally. It was Successful. The marked increase in Fledgling Begging Calls on 21 June most likely represents the fledging date for the Retry attempt. 

During this period, two sources of disturbance were documented:
• Feral pigs entered the nesting substrate, with eleven recordings of feral pig vocalizations between 24 March and 1 April and their presence was noted on 1 Apr during a site visit.
• Coyotes were present and may have used pig-created access paths; five recordings with coyote vocalizations were detected between 29 March and 7 May and site visits noted their presence near the colony from 29 Apr to 24 Jun.

Although these disturbances could have contributed to the colony's Partial Abandonment of its first breeding attempt, strong Male Chorus continued throughout the period when feral pigs were active, suggesting that feral pigs alone were not the primary driver of abandonment, and coyotes were present throughout the second successful breeding attempt.
column79:
Early-season activity is high, with strong Male Chorus throughout March and April. Activity drops abruptly on 25 April. A weak bout of Female Chatter in late April indicates that although most birds abandoned, a small number of females remained and nested. A site visit on 29 April confirmed Partial Abandonment: only ~50 birds remained from the original ~500, and only a few females were carrying food. Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls were not detected for this first attempt, but sparse Fledgling Begging Calls in late May–mid June indicate that a small number of nests succeeded, but the overall pattern is consistent with Partial Abandonment.

A second Retry attempt initiated later in the season and proceeded normally. It was successful. The marked increase in Fledgling Begging Calls on 21 June most likely represents the fledging date for the Retry attempt. 

During this period, two sources of disturbance were documented:
• Feral pigs entered the nesting substrate, with eleven recordings of feral pig vocalizations between 24 March and 1 April and their presence was noted on 1 Apr during a site visit.
• Coyotes were present and may have used pig-created access paths; five recordings with coyote vocalizations were detected between 29 March and 7 May and site visits noted their presence near the colony from 29 Apr to 24 Jun.

Although these disturbances could have contributed to the colony's Partial Abandonment of its first breeding attempt, strong Male Chorus continued throughout the period when feral pigs were active, suggesting that feral pigs alone were not the primary driver of abandonment, and coyotes were present throughout the second successful breeding attempt.

column78: Fledgling Begging Calls were detected during the deployment, confirming successful reproduction. Because the ARU was deployed after breeding had already begun and retrieved before Dispersal, the timing of breeding stages could not be determined.
column84: Small retirement community in the Mojave Desert. Artificial lake with an island in the center, with willows and cottonwoods, lawns, shrubbery. Surrounded by desert scrub on three sides, the fourth side has an irrigated field. In 2024, it was three-way grain hay oversown on alfalfa.

column78: Male Song and Male Chorus were detected, but no evidence of breeding was present.
column84: NEED

column78:
This colony’s breeding type was Unknown, with one breeding attempt. The outcome was Abandoned.
A large colony settled and initiated breeding, but all Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations ceased abruptly shortly after the onset of Brooding. The absence of Nestling or Fledgling Begging Calls following this decline indicates early abandonment. The timing of abandonment coincided with disturbance from helicopters detected acoustically at the site.
column84: Unit placed on the levee surrounding "Bridge St. pond" on the San Jacinto Wildlife Area.  To the west is private land, perennial ryegrass hay and alfalfa. To the south is the pond which is surrounded by a narrow band of willows and mulefat, and has a dense growth of cattails and bulrush in the pond itself. Beyond the pond is weedy fallow fields. To the east is Mystic Lake bed, mostly grown up in tall forbs, native and non-native. To the north is SJWA irrigated, weedy fields.

column78: Although Male Song was detected intermittently, Female Chatter and Begging Calls were absent. Acoustic evidence indicates that birds did not initiate a breeding attempt at this location.
column83: Himalayan blackberry, Bulrush or tule, Cattails
column84: Series of small copses of Himalayan blackberries alongside Yankee Slough, mostly on private conservation preserve, Yankee Slough Preserve, that is closed to the public and accessible only with permission.
